[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBlockQuote@@“Nobody ever won a chess game by resigning.” – Savielly Tartakower@@EndBlockQuote@@This course concentrates on selecting moves for White that are most commonly played by the 1600-2000 player.  Club players at this level will most likely encounter these during play.  Most of the moves I have selected for Black are based on the Chess engines at Chess.com and Lichess.com.  There are a few notable exceptions where I have selected moves that are one or two tenths of a pawn's value less.     o There is no clear understanding of the move by anyone other than AlphaZero and Super Grandmasters.  This means that there are no seemingly random a5 moves in the opening.     o Moves that begin lines of long expeditions that lie outside of the opening tenets of developing pieces, castling  (when appropriate)  , and connecting the rooks.     o Moves that make the line more difficult to remember.  Opening lines that are similar are more quickly and easily recalled.     o Moves that follow the most commonly used path when there are equally valid options.  By going down the road less traveled, your opponent has to spend more time catching up to your theory, and who does not want more time on their clock!  Once you pass the 2000 rating level it will be time to set this course aside and focus on more obscure and exacting lines.  For those of us who have not yet gotten to that level, this course will be useful in responding to lines most commonly played by our opponent. }
1. e4 c6
{ In this course we will be studying the Caro-Kann, a well known and solid defense by Black.  These first two moves define the name of the defense regardless of what happens next. }
2. d4
{ d4 is the most common response in this position.  The Lichess database offers over eight million games where this position exists, more than twice as many than the second most played response, Nf3  (to which d5 is the only reasonable response, then after an exchange of pawns White plays d4 and we have transposed to the Exchange Variation)  .  Also seen, in decreasing popularity, may be Bc4, Nc3, f4, and c4.  If the rare d3  (offered 3% of the time)  is played then White may be looking to play the King's Indian Attack }
2... d5
{ The only response at this point, and the position from where everything flows.  Some Ideas    Oftentimes this is the resulting pawn structure, where the two circled pawns get traded off, resulting in a queenside majority for White.  One strategy is to control the d5 square to prevent White from advancing the pawn.  Black can also look for a pawn break on c5 or e5.    
  Similar to the French Defense, Black's light-squared Bishop's value is diminished by the fact that, in this case, 5 of the 7 pawns are on light squares.  If Black has the opportunity to trade this Bishop off then that would offer Black an advantage.  Course Structure  The course is divided into two main sections, Opening Variations and Middlegame Play.    Opening Variations is a set of 18 lines that take one from the opening move to the end of the opening, where the pieces have been developed, King is castled, and the rooks linked.  One line ends prematurely, but the path forward is clear.   Following the final move of each line, blue lines indicate possible responses to White's next move and ideas going forward.  Green lines indicate White's most likely next move, when there are games in the database.  Middlegame Play continues with the positions at the end of each of the lines in the Opening Variations section.  These are the positions that are most likely to be encountered when actually playing, and can help with the question, 'What do I do now?.'  It is suggested that the first part be mastered before moving to the second part.  When possible, actual moves for White will be followed, along with Black's best response.  FEN notation of the ending position will be offered so that they can be copied into a chess engine for additional study. }
*

