1. e4 c6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@“Chess is beautiful enough to waste your life for.” – Hans Ree@@EndBlockQuote@@The Caro-Kann has been around seemingly forever.  The moves 1. e4 c6 are not out of the ordinary, so they have probably been played from the beginning, but we can only know for sure with recorded games.  The earliest recorded Caro-Kann by known players was played in 1856 by Somacarana, a Indian player who we only know through his nearly 200 games against John Cochrane.  Cochrane was a Scottish barrister and one of the best players in London, who recorded his games.  @@LinkStart@@http://bit.ly/CK_Cochrane@@LinkEnd@@   The namesake of the opening comes from British chess master Horatio Caro  (1862-1920)  and Marcus Kann  (1820-1886)  , an Austrian amateur player.  Caro, who spent most of his life in Berlin, was the first to analyze the move 1. ... c6 in his own magazine, Brüderschaft.  Marcus Kann is associated with the opening due to his impressive win against Jacques Mieses in the fourth German Chess Congress in 1885  (some references state that the game was 17 moves, chessgames has 24 - it does not really matter, as the game was basically over on move 17)  . @@LinkStart@@http://bit.ly/CK_MiesesVKann@@LinkEnd@@  He died a year before Caro's articles.  The first mention of the opening's name came in an article in Deutsche Schachzeitung  ('German Chess Player')  in 1890.  An interesting point is that the Fantasy Variation, which is sometimes thought of as a recent development  (my 1982 Modern Chess Openings mentions it as an afterthought, noting that it, 'loses impetus against a sensible defense')  , was recommended in the magazine as giving White an advantage.  There are numerous great players to have employed the Caro-Kann, like Capablanca  (@@LinkStart@@http://bit.ly/CK_Capablanca@@LinkEnd@@)  and Nimzowitsch  (@@LinkStart@@http://bit.ly/CK_Nimzowitsch@@LinkEnd@@)  , and they also played one another using the opening  (@@LinkStart@@https://bit.ly/CK_NimzowitschVCapablanca@@LinkEnd@@)  .  It has been played by Karpov, Botvinnik, Liren, Anand, Topalov, Nakamura, and on and on.  The opening has stood the test of time, and continues to be a staple response against 1. e4.  The next several sections of this chapter feature illustrative games. }
*

