[Black "What Variations Should I Concentrate On?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@“One doesn’t have to play well, it’s enough to play better than your opponent.” – Siegbert Tarrasch@@EndBlockQuote@@The purpose of this course is to prepare the average player to play against the opening 1. e4 by using the Caro-Kann defense. The moves of the Masters, while instructive, are less helpful than being ready for the moves of the players we are likely to encounter. To this end, we need to not only examine the variations, but also to know which variations should be emphasized. Variations that are rarely played by our opponents are considerably less important than the ones we are more likely to see.  This course covers six main variations of the Caro-Kann:   •	Advance Variation  •	Exchange Variation  •	Classical  •	Two Knights Variation  •	Hillbilly Attack  •	Fantasy Variation  The Lichess database allows me to see how many players play particular moves, and in the current instance we are concentrating on those rated 1600-2000 in the Rapid and Classic time controls. The actual selection includes games where at least one player is above 1600 and below 2200. This is their rating on Lichess, and since the website starts players at 1500 when they join, the ratings are a bit higher than one might expect over the board or on other websites.  Their database of players in this range gives us insight into what is being played at the average player's level and how often. The question one should be asking is that of the six variations, which should have down solid. Yes, the answer is, of course, all of them. However, one of the things that make us average players is that we cannot remember everything that comes our way, so knowing where to place our emphasis is helpful.  The following numbers are from 15 September 2021 and include only games selected of players with a rating of 1600-2000 in the Rapid and Classic time controls.  Caro-Kann 1. ... c6 2,404,798  2. d4 1,275,661 53.0% of games  2. Nf3 557,155 23.2% of games  2. Bc4 143,310 6.0% of games  2. Nc3 135,468 5.6% of games  2. Other 293,204 12.2% of games  We generally think of the “Caro-Kann” as White playing d4, Nf3, Bc4 or Nc3 on their second move, but there are a variety of odd alternatives, like f4, c4 and d3. These lines constitute a small percentage of the possibilities, so the primary continuations should be learned first.  Before moving on I will mention that according to the Lichess database, interestingly, of all possible second moves for White, the one with the highest winning percentage for White is c4, the Accelerated Panov Attack, winning 49% of the time and losing 45% of the time. Daniel Naroditsky can be seen dismantling this at @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fz9td9L2uIo@@LinkEnd@@.  Black usually plays d5 against whatever White plays, but not all the time.  2. d4 d5 96.6% of games  2. Nf3 d5 91.0% of games  2. Bc4 d5 86.4% of games  2. Nc3 d5 88.9% of games  Getting out of theory is certainly a possibility in any game.  For instance, even the most straightforward Advance Variation can immediately take an unusual turn.  For instance:   1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nf3?!  This strange third move has been played by at least three Masters, and two of the games resulted in draws. Certainly there is no way to prepare for such oddities.    We can, however, prepare for what can be reasonably expected, so here are the percentages for the most commonly played moves.  •	6.6% - Advance Variation  •	49.8% - Exchange Variation  •	29.2% - Classical  •	1.7% - Two Knights Variation  •	11.4% - Hillbilly Attack  •	1.4% - Fantasy Variation  Before finishing this section, however, I realized that these percentages worked for intermediate players, i.e. those who were selected in the Lichess database within a rating selection of 1600-2000.  I decided to look at the statistics of lower rated players, those who are selected just within the 1600 range.  It did not surprise me to find that the percentages were different.  •	7.8% - Advance Variation  •	29.0% - Exchange Variation  •	29.3% - Classical  •	1.2% - Two Knights Variation  •	31.4% - Hillbilly Attack  •	1.3% - Fantasy Variation  Regardless of your rating, the Exchange and Classical Variations are two variations that you are going to encounter on a regular basis.  If you are a lower rated player then the Hillbilly Attack will be an additional variation that will need to be known, as it will actually be seen as frequently as the other two.  This is good news because it is the easiest variation for Black to equalize and obtain a better position, so getting that variation down pat will definitely help you win games. }
