[Black "An Illustrative Game"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBlockQuote@@“The blunders are all there on the board, waiting to be made.” – Savielly Tartakower@@EndBlockQuote@@I thought that I would include a recent game where I used the Caro-Kann against e4, and my thoughts as I played it.  14 July 2020  brijesh0818 vs. GLSmyth }
1. e4 c6 2. Nf3
{ A possibility for the Two Knights Variation, or more probably transposing into another variation. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ More common is to transpose into the Exchange Variation, but this will be the Advance Variation. }
3... Bg4 { We commonly pin the Knight in this variation. } 4. d4 c5
{ Attacking the d-pawn.  White needs to decide whether to take the c5 pawn or protect the d4 pawn. }
5. c3 Nc6 6. b3
{ I was unclear what this move was meant to accomplish.  It is best to understand why an opponent plays a particular move so that those desires can be countered, but the only thing I could think of was that he would be playing Ba3 at some point.  If he was hoping to trade Bishops with me and revoke my Kingside castling rights, then this was too slow, as following thetheory my next move is to take the pawn on d4, then play e6. }
6... cxd4 { Just following the theory. } 7. cxd4 e6
{ e6 opens the diagonal for the Bishop and makes Ba3 a non-issue. } 8. Be2 Bb4+
{ Usually this Bishop ends up on either e7 or d6, but since the King was still exposed I decided to harass it. }
9. Bd2 Nge7
{ Not the best move on my part.  I was interesting in getting my pieces developed, but missed an opportunity:   9...Bxf3  10.Bxf3  Qb6  11.Bxb4  Qxb4+  12.Qd2  Qxd4  and Black wins a pawn. }
10. h3 { An unnecessary move, provoking me to rid myself of my bad Bishop. }
10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nf5 { Again, Qb6 would have been better. } 12. Bxb4
{ Relieving some of the pressure. } 12... Nxb4 13. O-O Nc6
{ Returning to where the Knight should be.  Now there is no way to properly protect the d-pawn. }
14. Nc3 Ncxd4 { I took with this Knight to open up the c file. } 15. Bg4 O-O
16. Bxf5
{ When down material, unless there is a good reason one should not trade down material. }
16... Nxf5 17. Re1 { Hoping to protect the e-pawn. } 17... Rc8
{ Putting a Rook on the open file. } 18. Rc1 Qa5
{ Putting pressure on the Knight and the a-pawn. } 19. Na4
{ A good move for White, but now his Knight is on the rim. } 19... b5
{ Forcing the Knight to move from its spot. } 20. b4
{ A counter attack on my Queen, but a bad idea.  I initially started to think about where to put my Queen, as I had not anticipated that move, but then I thought, 'Isn't that just a free pawn?' }
20... Qxb4 { Now White's position is starting to crumble. } 21. Rb1
{ This move does nothing, but the Knight is toast anyway. } 21... Qxa4 22. Qxa4
bxa4 { Doubling pawns is of no concern at this point. } 23. Rb4
{ An attack without teeth. } 23... Rc4 { I am fine with a trade of Rooks. } 24.
Rb7 Rc2 { And I am also fine with trading off one of my doubled pawns. } 25.
Reb1
{ A last gasp attempt to stay in the game.  I believe that he was hoping for   25...Rxa2  26.Rb8  Rxb8  27.Rxb8#  after all, it's never too late to blunder, but I was not going to allow that to happen. }
25... Rxa2 { Now my pawns are passed. } 26. Rb8
{ Yup, that was his plan, but it isn't going to happen. } 26... h6
{ Create an escape square just in case I might happen to need it. } 27. R8b7
{ He can get one pawn, but he cannot get both. } 27... Rc8
{ With this move my opponent resigned.  Since my King was safe, my plan was to play Rcc2, and with doubled Rooks begin to pillage his pawns.  I did not play any spectacular or particularly insightful moves in this game, yet White's move 6 began his decline, and I simply played strong and steady moves until his position collapsed.  At the level of the average player it is not about trying to be brilliant, but about making fewer mistakes than one's opponent. }
