[White "Preface"]
[Black "Generalizations"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBlockQuote@@“Those who say they understand chess, understand nothing.” – Robert Hübner@@EndBlockQuote@@   1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  Nd5  3.Nf3  0-1 }
1. e4 c6
{ I was watching Ginger GM play a speed run  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y2mhbgubuvQ@@LinkEnd@@)  , and at the end of the game above I literally broke into laughter.  It was a three-minute game and his opponent was premoving, as their first three moves took only one second off the clock.  To save embarrassing his opponent I will not give their name, but simply state that they were rated 1911, so this was a strong player.   Having a basic setup is oftentimes a great idea, but there may be circumstances where those initial ideas need to remain flexible.  In this section, I will discuss commonalities in the positions that are oftentimes reached in our Caro-Kann course, and will offer some ideas on piece placement.  As per the previous paragraph, it must be emphasized that there will always be exceptions, so none of the following is carved in stone.  One must be willing to alter plans to accommodate whatever situation arises.  These observations pertain only to the variations that are followed in this course.  We have avoided a fair amount of theory by occasionally deciding to follow less commonly traveled lines, so the situations outlined may be different from other Caro-Kann games.  King  The King gets castled Kingside.  The pawn structure in front of it is usually very solid so there is safety there. It is usually castled within the first ten moves, though in the Advance Variation it may take a little longer.  In cases where a trade has left the g file open, the King will oftentimes move to the h file so that the square it was on can be used by a Rook on the semi-open file.  Queen  The Queen is usually developed after all of the minor pieces have left the back rank.  In the Exchange Variation, it oftentimes finds a home on c7, which is a good location since that file is open on Black's side of the board.  Bishops  White's placement of their King's Knight is usually on f3, and Black, if possible, pins the Knight with its light-squared Bishop to the Queen via Bg4.  When the Knight is not on f3, if the Bishop has the support of its Knight on f6 then it can directly attack the Queen.  White will usually play h3, forcing Black to either take the Knight or drop back to h5.  The course identifies the best course of action in each variation, however, in a real game the correct move may be difficult to remember. I tested this decision in each of the valuations in the course and found that if Black made the wrong decision and moved the Bishop to h5 then at worst they lose 0.2 pawns.  However, if they make the wrong decision by taking the Knight then they could lose 1.1 pawns.  In real life, when in doubt, drop the Bishop back.   The natural placement for Black's dark-squared Bishop is on d6, with it sometimes going to e7.  When it does go to e7 it is not so much protecting a Knight on f6 with the fear of the doubling of pawns if the Knight is taken as it is for positional reasons.  Knights  f6 and c6 are the starting points for the Knights, except for the Classical Variations, where they are developed to d7 since Black has a pawn on c6.  In the Advance Variations, the Knight cannot be developed to f6 because of White's pawn on e5, so it travels to e7, then f5, which is commonly seen in the French Defense.  Pawns  Black normally has more light-squared pawns than dark-squared pawns, a trend that begins from its very first move.  By stripping away the pieces and showing just pawns, we can see what the pawn structures for both sides may look like.  We will examine the Exchange, Advance, and Classical Variations, and are including the Panov-Botvinnik Attack because although part of the Exchange Variation, the pawn structure is closer to that of the Classical Variation.  Exchange Variation    The pawn structure of the Exchange Variation is very even.  White is missing the e-pawn and Black the b or c pawn, but they are each taking up the same amount of space on the board.  Black's g-pawn may be used to push White's light-squared Bishop away.  If that is the case then the g and h-pawns can be used in a Kingside attack.  The d, e, and f-pawns generally stay where they are through the middlegame, although if the e-pawn can advance then there can be a great advantage in doing so.  The a and b or c-pawns  (whichever one remains following the opening)  generally stay put.  They may be used later in the game to disrupt White's Queenside majority  Advance Variation    The pawn structure here shows that White has a decided space advantage.  However, the open c file can give Black chances to attack White's weak d-pawn.  For the most part, Black's f, g, and h-pawns remain where they are.  A major exception to that is when the f-pawn is used to attack White's advanced e-pawn.  After an exchange, the semi-open file offers space for a Rook to work.  The e and d-pawns remain where they are, holding down Black's center.  As is the case with the Exchange Variation, if Black can play e4 then there is a real advantage to be had.  The a and b-pawns remain in place.  As they are matched by White's a and b-pawns and the c file is open, they do not have much chance for activity until much later in the game.  Classical and Panov-Botvinnik Variations    I put these two together because the pawn structures are similar in the respect that Black is missing their d and either e or c-pawns.  In both cases, White's d-pawn has an unobstructed path if it can find a way to remove Black's c or e-pawn.  This does not happen in our example lines in the Classical - Korchnoi and Panov-Botvinnik Attack Variations but is a threat in the Classical 6. Nf3 Variation.  For the most part, these pawns do not play much of a role in the middlegame, but are more of an endgame tool. }
