[Black "Advance Variation 3. ... c5 4. c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ e5 is White's most common response to this position.  There is a boatload of theory connected with this move, but with Black's next move the vast majority of that will go out the window. }
3... c5
{ Stockfish 13 shows Bf5 and c5 as being equally good moves.  Bf5 is considerably more popular in the Masters games, and the 1600-2000 games it is played 83% of the time.  If they are equally good then why not go with the line that is less familiar to White?  c5 removes the vast majority of theory White may have learned when preparing to play against the Caro-Kann, so by learning the Advance lines well, Black can be pounding out the moves while White is trying to navigate what they think may work best. }
4. c3 { Four times as popular as dxc5. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4
{ Black is reasonably not going to be able to add more attackers at this point, so it is a good time to go ahead and strike into the line. }
6. cxd4 Bg4
{ Getting the Bishop out before closing the diagonal.  Pinning this Knight will be a recurring theme in this opening. }
7. Be2 e6
{ At times the Caro-Kann position can resemble that of a French position, with the important exception that the light-squared Bishop is out there doing something, as opposed to sitting on the back rank trying to get into the game. }
8. O-O Nge7
{ A natural square for the King's Knight, with the intention of going to g6 or f5.    8...Bxf3 is not as strong, and our concentration is to activate our pieces and get castled.  The line would continue:   8...Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Qb6  10.Be3  Qxb2  and an equal position. }
9. Nc3
{ Not the best move, but the most popular.  Nbd2 is better because it offers cover for Qb3 if Black decides to play Qb6, but is the fifth most popular move. }
9... Nf5
{ Adding a second attacker to d4.   If  9.h3  then  9...Bxf3  Rc8 is an equally valid alternative. }
10. Be3 Be7
{ There are a number of possibilities here, Be7 is selected as a developing move to give Black the option to castle.   Bb4 is is a perfectly acceptable alternative. }
11. h3 Bxf3
{ In these situations it is more common to take the Knight than it is to slide back to h5.  Both are fine in this position.  Black having five of its seven pawns on light-colored squares is common, so trading it off is oftentimes advantageous.  In both cases the position ends up being equal.   11...Bh5  12.g4  Nxe3  13.fxe3  Bg6 }
12. Bxf3 O-O
{ Evaluation: -0.2  Bg5 is, by two tenths of a pawn, the top engine move.  However, it is probably best to get in the habit of first being comfortably castled unless there is a real advantage to not doing so.  Under the arrow buttons below the board is the FEN notation for this position.  This can be placed into a chess engine so that you can play against it.  Even though you may not encounter the exact position in your games, you have the opportunity to practice playing against the general idea.  Additionally, this position, as will be the case with all end positions in this chapter, will appear as an initial position in the Middlegame Play chapter.  This will offer additional practice in playing this position.  Games from this position:   @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/pQyatU7u@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/CjKwIhoB@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/TbndhhBc@@LinkEnd@@ }
