[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Advance Variation 3. ... c5 4. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6
{ For players of the French who are switching to the Caro-Kann because they are tired of trying to resolve the difficulties with the French Bishop  (that would be me!)  , this move is counterintuitive.  It blocks in the light-squared Bishop, which is an issue that will need to be resolved at some point.  But it is the beginning of pressure on a pawn that really does need to be retaken. }
5. Be3 Nd7 { A second attacker of the c5 pawn. } 6. Bb5 Ne7
{ A move that will eventually remove the dark-squared Bishop as a defender. }
7. Nf3 { Better for White would have been Bd4. } 7... Nf5 8. Bd4
{ Again, not the best move, but the most popular. } 8... Qa5+
{ Positioning the Queen to eventually retake the pawn. } 9. Nc3 a6
{ Time to remove the pin on the Knight. } 10. Bxd7+ Bxd7
{ White has done Black a favor in offering a meaningful means of developing the light-squared Bishop. }
11. O-O Nxd4 { Removing the defender of c5. } 12. Nxd4 Qxc5
{ Evaluation: -0.2  Taking with the Queen is very slightly better than with the Bishop, as it places the piece on a more useful square.  Taking with the Bishop is fine.  The Rooks will contest for the c-file and there may be a better place to locate Black's light-squared Bishop.  Games in this position:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/9bBdkQjR@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/UGriQRqD@@LinkEnd@@ }
