[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Exchange Variation 4. Nf3 5. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5
{ The Exchange Variation is White's second most popular response to the Caro-Kann, even more popular than the Classical Variation.  In the French Defense when someone plays the Exchange Variation I wonder if I should simply offer them a draw at that moment, as they have decided to play the most boring choice possible.  This is not the case with the Caro-Kann, as can be seen by the number of variations following this choice. }
3... cxd5 4. Nf3
{ This is White's most popular move in this position.  Second most popular is c4 and third is Bd3, which will both be examined later. }
4... Nf6
{ With the exception of the Advance and Fantasy Variations, this Knight will always be placed on f6.  The engine says that Nc6 is one tenth of a pawn stronger, but we will get used to initially placing the King's Knight here, which will give us less to have to remember.    With the abilities of the average club player, this small of a difference is inconsequential  (certainly not the case in the higher levels)  .  With the abilities of Masters, they also agree that this is a better move. }
5. Bd3
{ The first of the two most popular lines played by the 1600-2000 crowd. } 5...
Bg4
{ Again, the engine shows Nc6 to be one tenth of a pawn stronger than this move. Pinning the Knight here is another recurring theme - the other Knight will make it's way out in a moment.  The purpose of moving the Bishop here is less to pin the Knight to the Queen, but more to move it outside of e6 when it is played, and to possibly exchange it with White's light-squared Bishop.  Masters games show that they prefer Nc6 by a slight margin, but Karpov played Bg4 in this position against Judit Polgar  (and won)  in 1995, so it is certainly a good move.  Not to worry, however, Nc6 will be played next. }
6. O-O Nc6
{ Developing the Knight in such a way that White will be required to do something to protect their d4 pawn, which currently cannot be defended. }
7. c3 e6
{ The e-pawn initially belongs on this pawn in nearly every version of the Caro-Kann. }
8. Bg5 Bd6
{ This is a very common placement for Black's Bishop, which will be seen in numerous variations. }
9. Nbd2 O-O
{ Finishes development.  There are a host of alternative moves, namely h6, Bh5, Rc8, and Qc7.  Evaluation: 0.0  Numerous games in this position, for instance:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/ed6C5tkr@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/yQ9FrWyk@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/L9Thpgit@@LinkEnd@@ }
