[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Exchange Variation 4. Nf3 5. Nc3 8. h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bg4
{ Generally speaking, if you can pin this Knight then do so.  This is a common move in most variations that are being followed. }
6. Be2 Nc6
{ Since White's light-squared Bishop has already been given the task of supporting the Knight on f3, it is unlikely that it will be redeployed to b5 to pin the Knight. }
7. O-O e6 8. h3 Bxf3
{ Bringing the Bishop back to h5 is a tenth of a pawn stronger.  The trade will probably happen anyway, so it is fine getting this out of the way.   8...Bh5  9.Bg5  Bd6  10.Nb5  Be7  11.Ne5  Bxe2 }
9. Bxf3 Bd6
{ The engine has Rc8 a tenth of a pawn stronger.  If we are to emphasize development then getting the dark squared Bishop to its spot works well. }
10. Bg5
{ Definitely not the best move, but the most likely to be encountered. } 10...
O-O
{ Evaluation: -0.3  Again, the engine prefers Rc8 as a tenth of a pawn stronger.  Now that we are developed we can add this to our candidate moves.  A fairly even game where Black has a very slight edge.  Both sides have possibilities for attacking in this positional game.  Games in this position:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/J4VkIFex@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/81tdz9j3@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/eYiqj5PI@@LinkEnd@@ }
