1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ White's second most popular move in this position. } 4... Nf6
{ g6 is also a move, but if White takes the pawn then that makes things slightly more difficult. }
5. Nc3 g6
{ We are going to fianchetto the Bishop.  This is actually one tenth of a pawn weaker than e6, but as a French Opening player who is learning the Caro-Kann because of the problems dealing with the locked in light-squared Bishop, it does not feel right to create this problem. }
6. Nf3 Bg7 7. cxd5 { c5 is also a move, but is seldom played. } 7... Nxd5
{ Castling is also an option, but why complicate things? } 8. Bc4 Nxc3
{ Nb6 is the more popular move, but the engines prefer this forcing move. } 9.
bxc3 Qc7
{ Castling is a possibility, and the more popular move, but the engine prefers Qc7 because it is develops the Queen with a forcing move, attacking the c4 Bishop. }
10. Qb3 O-O 11. O-O
{ Bd5 is also a possibility, but nobody under 2000 plays it. } 11... Nc6
{ Time to get the other pieces out. } 12. Bd3 Bg4
{ Be6 is the choice of the engine.  This blocks the e-pawn and creates a one move threat on White's Queen.  At the cost of two tenths of a pawn, putting the Bishop on g4 not only completes development, but also threatens to ruin White's pawn structure, something White will need to address before moving forward. }
13. Nd2 Rfd8
{ Evaluation: -0.7  No games from this position.  In the only game from the previous position Black played Rac8, which is almost as good. }
