1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ Bd3 is the strongest square to place this Bishop.  It prevents Black from developing its light-squared Bishop to f5. }
4... Nf6 5. c3 Bg4
{ The only place for the light-squared Bishop.  Black needs to get this Bishop out so that it can play e6, finish developing, and get castled.  White will need to decide whether to offer the Knight to be pinned, move the Bishop a second time in the opening to meet the attack, weaken their Kingside pawn structure with f3, or move the Queen. }
6. Qb3 { The most popular choice for White, a 2-1 choice over Nf3. } 6... Qc7
{ Qd7 is equally good - I just don't like setting White up for the pin. } 7.
Ne2 { h3 will also be seen, and possibly Bg5. } 7... Bxe2
{ Trading off the light-squared Bishop favors Black, as the upcoming move e6 will give Black five of seven pawns on light squares. }
8. Bxe2 e6
{ From here on out it is just standard development, putting the pieces where they are most commonly placed in this opening. }
9. O-O Bd6 10. h3 O-O 11. Nd2 Nc6
