1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. h3
{ The final variation.  Unlike all of the other Exchange Variations, we will not be able to move our light-squared Bishop to pin an f3 Knight or attack the Queen.  Another strategy will need to take place. }
5... g6
{ This, and the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, will have us fianchetto our Bishop.  There will be a seemingly unusual way of getting the light-squared Bishop into play which may appear sketchy, but is quite solid. }
6. Nf3 Bg7
{ This is followed by typical developing moves that we have seen for this opening. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nc6
{ By a tenth of a pawn the engine prefers what will be our next move.  It also results in the same position within a few moves. }
9. c3 Bf5
{ At the 1600-2000 level, White may think of this as a bad move.  However, note that five of seven pawns are on light squares - after Black plays e6 it will be six out of seven. }
10. Bxf5
{ White's best move is to slide the Bishop back to f1, or perhaps move it to b5, or e2.  However, try telling that to a 1600-2000 player. }
10... gxf5
{ Black's pawn structure is not destroyed, e6 will bring everything together, and Black will have an open file on which is can place its Rook, which will stare at White's King. }
11. Bf4
{ White has much to choose from, like Nbd2, Ne5 and Bg5, but Bf4 is the most popular. }
11... e6
{ Evaluation: +0.1  Tying everything together.  Note that after moving the King to h8, when the Rook is placed on g8 it is staring at White's King, as happened in the first game listed below.   Games from this position:  12. Ne5 @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/RiJhIPCY@@LinkEnd@@  12. Ne5 @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/n23aSOQP@@LinkEnd@@  12. Ne5 @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/jGbXuk1G@@LinkEnd@@ }
