1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Nd2 results in the same continuation after Blacks takes the pawn on d4. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Karpov preferred playing the solid Nbd7 here, then Ngf6, preventing the doubling of the pawns in the variation we will be using.  If one decides to go this route, they need to watch for a well known trap.   4...Nd7  5.Qe2  Ngf6?  a natural move  6.Nd6# }
5. Nxf6+
{ The overwhelming choice, and White's best option.  However, White can set a trap that over 150 players have fallen for in the Lichess database.  Whenever a player brings out their Queen early in the game one should be suspicious.   5.Qd3  Bf5?  6.Nxf6+  exf6  7.Qxf5  For what it is worth, the correct response is the simple Nxe4.   5.Qd3  Nxe4 }
5... exf6
{ The decision of which pawn to take with will be a matter of player's style.  Taking with the e-pawn is considered to be 'drawish.'  In the second chapter, where we look at continuations following the opening, we will see that this is the case, but at the 1600-2000 level there are yet mistakes to be made, so anything can happen.  I chose this line because it is safer than capturing with the g-pawn.  My strategy is somewhat like the Hippocratic oath, 'Do no harm,' so safety is the first consideration.  Once this variation is mastered then one can look into taking with the g-pawn, which will result in more interesting games. }
6. Nf3
{ Masters are more prone to play c3.  Their second choice is Bc4.  1600-2000 players greatly prefer Nf3.  This line is so similar to the c3 line that there is no need to follow it basically to the same place. }
6... Bd6 { This is best almost regardless of White's move. } 7. Bd3 O-O
{ The engine suggests Na6 as the best move by one tenth of a pawn, which may work as a novelty.  If you do not mind seeing your Knight on the rim, then baiting White to take the Knight leads to the following:   7...Na6  8.Bxa6  Qa5+  Of the 103 games in Lichess's Masters database, this move has never been played, while O-O has been played 93 times. }
8. O-O Bg4 9. h3 Bh5
{ The only reasonable move.  If chased it can always move to g6 without concerns of pawns being doubled.  Also, Black  does not have a preponderance of pawns on light-colored squares. }
10. c3 Nd7 11. Re1 Re8
{ By a tenth of a pawn the engine recommends Qc7, then wants to play c5.  We have chosen development into the open file before pushing ahead. }
12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Be3 Rd8 { Evaluation: 0.0  No games in this position. } *

