[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Classical - Korchnoi Variation 6. c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3
{ Not the most popular for lower rated players, but the best move available to White. }
6... Bd6
{ The engine prefers either Bf5, g6, and Be7 by one tenth of a pawn over Bd6.  Masters prefer Bd6 ten times more than Bf5, one hundred times more than g6, and three hundred times more than Be7.  We are choosing to play Bd6 partially because in this opening we usually play this move early, and partially because it is what Masters play. }
7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+
{ Another case where the engine differs from what Masters play.  It says that h6 and g6 evaluate two tenths of a pawn better, and Kh8 and h5 one tenth of a pawn stronger.  Masters prefer developing the Rook with tempo and prefer it:   4 times more than h6  10 times more than g6  15 times more than Kh8  41 times more than h5  Again, we side with the Masters.  e2 is the typical placement for White's Knight in this situation, but Black may as well force it and take the file with tempo.  This also opens up the f8 square, which may be used by the Knight in the future. }
9. Ne2 h6
{ I love the engines, but they can be frustrating.  Stockfish 14 on Lichess offers h5 as two tenths of a pawn stronger than h6.  Stockfish 14 at @@LinkStart@@https://nextchessmove.com/@@LinkEnd@@ claims h6 to be the strongest move in this position.  It is a flip of the coin as to which one to play, but I have a feeling that the average player is more comfortable with h6. }
10. O-O Nd7 11. Bf4
{ Not White'se best move, but the choice of lower and higher rated players.  The engines prefer placing the Bishop on d2. }
11... Nf8
{ Black has no choice but to trade its dark-squared Bishop.  Black does multiple things with this move - it allows the trade to be made where the Queen will be more centralized, it clears the way to develop the light-squared Bishop, and offers the opportunity to later place the Knight on g6 or e6, which are more useful squares.  All that said, Nf8 is almost certain to be the move here regardless of White's previous move. }
12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ng3 Bd7
{ There are two continuations that are two tenths of a pawn better than Bd7.   13...Qf4  14.Rfe1  Bd7  15.Nf1  Rad8  16.Rxe8  Rxe8  17.a4  Ne6  18.g3  Qd6  19.Ne3  Ng5  20.h4  Rxe3  21.hxg5   13...Qc7  14.Rfe1  Be6  15.Re3  Rad8  16.h4  Bd7  17.Rxe8  Rxe8  18.a4  c5  19.dxc5  Qxc5  20.b4  Qc7  21.a5  Masters have no use for either of these moves Queen moves.  I struggle to figure out why relocating the Queen offers a better position than developing the Bishop so that the Rooks can connect.  If the reader understands the logic behind the recommended Queen moves then I would suggest that they may be a better alternative.  Lacking that, it is better to have a reason behind making a move than playing an engine move that is not understood.  Bd7 allows the Rooks to connect.  White will probably bring one of their Rooks to e1, and after exchanging Rooks, Black's Knight will probably end up on e6 or g6.  Evaluation: +0.4  This is a challenging line for Black, probably the most problematic of all in the course.  White won both example games below, but Black's defeat had nothing to do with the opening.  In the initial game things were fairly even until Black made significant blunders on moves 20, 21, and 23.  In the second example Black made a seven pawn blunder on move 19, and never recovered.  In the case of the average player, mistakes and blunders determine the fate of the game more than slight two tenths of a pawn inaccuracies.  Games in this position:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/z2LqR5QQ@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/l4i8TkNb@@LinkEnd@@ }
