[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Two Knights Variation 6. d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nc3
{ The Two Knights Variation is a valid option for the White player, but at the 1600-2000 level offers numerous possibilities to play inaccurate moves.  When Black sees this move it is almost as if seeing a puzzle in this position that states, 'Black to move and move to obtain strong advantage.' }
2... d5 3. Nf3 Bg4
{ By far, the most common move for Black is dxe4.  There are two advantages to playing Bg4.  The first is that Black has moved away from White's expectations, and perhaps, their preparation.  Also, by a whisker, the engines show that Bg4 is simply a better move.  The other is that this move avoids a well known trap that can send Black home early.  If you can avoid a trap in the first place by naturally playing a better move then that is an all around win.  Check out these moves.   3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nf6  5.Qe2  Nbd7  6.Nd6# }
4. h3 Bxf3
{ Moving the Bishop back to h5 is okay, but not as strong.   4...Bh5  5.exd5  cxd5  6.g4  Bg6  7.Ne5  Nc6  8.d4  e6  9.h4  h6  10.Nxg6  fxg6  Black ends up with an opened Kingside and a weak e-pawn. }
5. Qxf3 e6
{ Black has gotten rid of the bad Bishop and strengthened the light squares. }
6. d4
{ The most common move in this variation.  There is a line where White plays d3 that can be turned to Black's advantage if White is feeling greedy.   6.d3  Bb4  7.Qg3  Nf6  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qh6  d4  10.a3  Bf8! }
6... Nf6 7. e5 Nfd7 8. Bd3 c5
{ It is a common theme in the Caro-Kann to attack the d4 pawn with c5, and when it is protected add a layer of attack with the Queenside Knight.  Of course, if White is willing to take the pawn then Black can retake with the dark-squared Bishop, developing it. }
9. Be3
{ dxc5 is the correct move in this position, but in the 1600-2000 section the errant Be3 is played more than three times more often. }
9... Nc6 { Locking in the advantage of White's error. } 10. Bb5
{ Actually, in 1600-2000 games, White is more likely to compound their problems with   10.dxc5  than play the much better Bb5.  If this happens, Black simply plays d4, forking the Bishop and Knight. }
10... cxd4
{ A common thread is to take at this point, when Black has no realistic hope of adding more attackers to the d4 pawn than White can successfully defend.  Taking with the Knight is an equally valid option. }
11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bxd4 c5
{ Despite White removing the attacker, like the Walking Dead, the c-pawn arises to again attack the d4 square. }
13. Be3
{ Again, I diverge from showing the most likely move for the 1600-2000 player, which would have been Nxd5.   Be3 is White's best chance. }
13... Nxe5
{ Evaluation: -2.8  No need to continue from here.  Black has an easy path to fork the Bishop and Knight, develop the Bishop, and castle.  No games in this position. }
