1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ The Hillbilly Attack is not one of White's best replies to the Caro-Kann.  By the time Black is developed they should have an advantageous position.  After all, there is a reason why Masters choose to employ the Hillbilly Attack only 0.02% of the time against the Caro-Kann. }
2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ This forces White to either retreat or continue by checking the King on b5. }
4. Bb3
{ Retreating is the more common move by a 2-1 margin.  Also possible is to attack the King via:   4.Bb5+  , which will be examined in another variation. }
4... Nf6 5. d4 Bg4
{ Only the third most commonly played move by Black.  Does this attack make sense? }
6. f3
{ This is White's most common move, almost 2-1, over Nf3.  I have also had Ne2 played against me, which is fine, but not as strong as f3 or Nf3. }
6... Bd7
{ In games played at the 1600-2000 level, the two most common moves are   6...Bf5  and  6...Bh5  Only 3% of the time does Black play Bd7, which along with Bf5 are the two strongest moves.  The most popular move in this position, Bf5, is completely fine.  However, it may be better to play the line my opponent may be less prepared for, and will have to take more time from their clock to figure the best response.  At first it looks like Black has wasted time with a one move attack that was thwarted by a pawn.  However, the reason for Bg4 was to provoke f3.  This weakens White's Kingside, removes the natural square for the Knight, and if White castles on that side then Black can place their Queen on the very natural b6 square, x-raying the King through the center pawn. }
7. Ne2 { The natural location for White Knight is taken by a pawn. } 7... e6 8.
O-O Be7 { The Bishop could also be placed on d6. } 9. c3 O-O 10. Ng3 b5
{ b5 is the strongest engine move.  In the only game in the Lichess database that contains the previous position  (@@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/nMKRju4D@@LinkEnd@@)  Black played Qc7, so from this point forward we will be looking at best moves. }
11. f4 g6
{ This reinforces protection of the f5 square to discourage the additional advancement of White's f-pawn. }
12. a3 a5 { Black continues the Queenside attack. } 13. Nd2 Nc6
{ Evaluation: -1.0  Black has opened up an attack on the Queenside and White is still two moves away from developing their dark-squared Bishop.  Black has an advantage that should be retained with a continued attack.  No games in this position. }
