1. e4 c6 2. Bc4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb5+
{ A more confrontational and less popular move than Bb3, but equally ineffective. }
4... Bd7 { A move that more actively attacks White's only developed piece. } 5.
Bxd7+
{ It is possible, but unlikely, that White will instead play:   5.Qe2  or  5.Nc3  Best for White is to either trade the Bishops or return to e2. }
5... Nxd7
{ The best move, as opposed to taking with the Queen.  This develops the Knight to a natural square and opens things up so that the Queenside Rook can get into the game. }
6. Nf3 Ngf6 7. O-O e6 8. d4 Bd6
{ The best place for the Bishop at this point. The Knight on d6 is protecting the f6 Knight from a future pin. }
9. Bg5 Qb6
{ Now that the dark-squared Bishop has left its post, its time to put pressure on b2. }
10. b3 Qa6
{ Now that White has weakened the Queenside pawns, the Queen can be placed on a more useful square.  With this move there are no games in the Lichess database. From here we look at best moves. }
11. Nbd2 h6 { Kicking the Bishop back. } 12. Be3 O-O
{ Evaluation: -0.6  Stockfish 14 on Lichess says that the best move is b6, Stockfish 14 on nextchessmove.com/ says it is to castle.  The latter makes more sense to me.  Castling offers Black the ability to move the King's Rook to the Queenside for possible invasion there. This position is comfortable for Black.  No games in this position. }
