[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Opening Variations"]
[Black "Fantasy Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3
{ f3 is the Fantasy Variation, which is unlikely, but needs to be examined. }
3... dxe4
{ This is the most popular continuation for Black, with e6, g6 and Qb6 being alternatives.  It is not absolutely the strongest continuation for Black, but immediately solves the problem of having no proper square for the light-squared Bishop. }
4. fxe4 e5
{ The best move by far.  If White takes the pawn thinking that that may be compensation following an exchange of Queens, Black can instead play Qh4+.  The e4 pawn will then fall, and Black can carefully develop using White's exposed King to gain tempo.   5.dxe5  Qh4+  6.Kd2  Qf4+  7.Ke1  Qxe5 }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ The best move, with Be6 a close second.  The reason that Be6 is a good move, as we usually pin the Knight when possible, is that it prevents White from playing Bc4.  As will be seen when Black makes move 6, playing the natural move could result in huge complications - Be6 prevents this.  Black may think of taking the pawn, but that can offer poor results.   5...exd4  6.Bc4  Bc5  Trying to protect the pawn with the Bishop  7.O-O  Nf6  8.Ng5  O-O  9.Bxf7+  Rxf7  10.Nxf7  The King cannot take the Knight.  Kxf7  11.Qh5+  Kg8  12.Qxc5  Trying to hold the pawn with c5 does not help either.   5...exd4  6.Bc4  c5  7.O-O  Be6  8.Bxe6  fxe6  9.Ng5  Qd7  10.Nf7  and the Rook falls. }
6. Bc4
{ An important point here is that whenever one sees a Bishop on c4 and a Knight on f3, red flags should fly and possible tactics should be observed.  Even though White's Knight is pinned, that may not matter if it can be moved with check.  A nonchalant move could result in a disastrous loss of material. }
6... Nd7
{ An instructive move.  If Nd7 is not played, White can take the pawn on f7 with check, and after the King takes, Nxe5+ and Black's Bishop falls.  Black can play Ke7  (unlikely at the 1600-2000 level)  , after which White simply plays Bb3 and enjoys playing a position where Black has an isolated King pawn, and the King is stuck in the center, blocking in its dark-squared Bishop, without the possibility of castling.   6...Nf6  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Nxe5+  Ke8  9.Nxg4  By placing the Knight on d7, the tactics do not work because at the end of the sequence, the Knight that had been placed on d7 ends up on e5, protecting the Bishop.  White would end up trading two pieces for two pawns.  
Bh5 and Qe7 are also possible, but vastly inferior. }
7. O-O Ngf6 8. c3 Bd6
{ By the way, Black cannot take the e4 pawn.   8...Nxe4  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Nxe5+  Ke8  11.Qxg4 }
9. Bg5 O-O
{ Evaluation: 0.0  Games in this position:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/CxtE7c7q@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/u27OdJwS@@LinkEnd@@  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/mL26o2O2@@LinkEnd@@ }
