[Result "*"]

{ The best way to work with this Middlegame section is to return to the Course Options and change the Reps to 1 and click the infinity symbol next to the Time option.  The idea is not to memorize moves in positions you will never see, but to examine positions that will be similar to the ones you will be seeing and become familiar with the directions they may take.  It is ludicrous to be limited to 60 seconds to make a response, unless you are a Blitz or Bullet player, so setting the Time to infinity gives you time to understand what is in front of you, instead of trying to make a hasty move. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O
Nge7 9. Nc3 Nf5 10. Be3 Be7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 O-O 13. a3
{ This is the most commonly played move in this position, an inaccuracy that costs White time.  Better would have been Qd3, Rb1 or Bg4, the last of which will be examined in another line. }
13... Rc8 { Developing to an open file. } 14. Rc1 Bg5
{ There were several games in the previous position, but none of them responded in the best way by playing Bg5  (although all but one went on to win, and the other one a draw)  .  From this point we are looking at best moves. }
15. Qd3 g6
{ A move that initially looks strange but has purpose.  One plan for Black would be to play Na5, then eventually Nc4. However, without the g6 support to the f5 Knight it cannot work.   15...Na5  16.Nxd5  taking back immediately is a mistake  exd5  17.Qxf5  Even making the best move following the pawn capture is not good.   15...Na5  16.Nxd5  Nc6  At the beginning of this sequence the valuation was -0.7.  Following these two examples the valuations are respectively +4.5 and +0.6. }
16. Rc2 Bxe3
{ Both dark-squared Bishops are good.  However, as Black has six of seven pawns on light squares, trading at this point makes White's light-squared Bishop very bad. }
17. fxe3 Qg5 { The beginnings of an attack on White's Kingside. } 18. Re1 f6
{ Black would like to open a line for attack as well as chip away at White's center, offering White the choice to take the pawn or end up with isolated doubled pawns. }
19. exf6 Rxf6 20. Bg4 {  } 20... Nh6
{ Evaluation: -0.9  Although Black is doing well, it will take exacting play to tip the scales completely.  As was the case in the previous chapter, under the move arrows below the board is the FEN notation for the position.  This can be copied into a chess engine and play against it.  Even though you may not encounter the exact position, you will have the opportunity to practice playing against the general idea. }
