Ne5 Bxe2 9. Nxe2 Qc7 10. Bf4 Bd6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. c3 O-O 14. Qd3
{ The most popular move from this position. } 14... c5
{ It is difficult for White to not trade its most forward central pawn in this situation.  If White insists upon holding onto the pawn then Black can simply make the trade themselves at the opportune time.   15.b3  Rac8  16.h3  h6  17.Rfb1  Rc7  18.Qe3  Rfc8  19.a4  cxd4  White can take back with either the Queen or the Knight, and Black has an advantage. }
15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Nd4 Rfc8
{ With this move we follow the game located at @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/tJbcGE8R@@LinkEnd@@. }
17. Rfe1 Ne4
{ With White moving the Rook. the f2 pawn is only protected by the King.  Moving White's Knight out of the way should be easy. }
18. Re3 a5 { Preventing White from playing b4. } 19. Rh3
{ A blunder when there were other moves that would have offered better chances, like h3, Re2 or Rc1. }
19... e5
{ Evaluation: -4.5  In the game we have been following, Black did not take advantage of this blunder and played g6. Pushing e5 can result in the following devastation:   19...e5  20.Nc2  Qxf2+  21.Kh1  Rab8  22.Rf3  Rxb2  If the Rook takes the Queen then retaking forks the King and Queen. }
