[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "BONUS: The Oddballs"]
[Black "2. d3 - Breyer Variation"]
[Result "*"]

{ Of the 2,000,000+ Caro-Kann games in the Lichess database that involve games of players rated 1600-2000 in Rapid and Classical time limits, this course has covered nearly 90% of the most popular responses.  The remaining 10% means that there may be times when something out of the ordinary is thrown at you.  I had not planned to do this chapter, but recently an opponent offered the Breyer Variation against me, something that one at the 1600-2000 level will see about one out of every 50 Caro-Kann games.  I was immediately out of theory and did not make the best move on move 3.  Fortunately, I was able to recover from the slight misstep and win the game.  I have decided to add some of these offbeat continuations so that you can at least get past move 3 without a misstep. }
1. e4 c6 2. d3 { This denotes the Breyer variation. } 2... d5 3. Nd2 e5
{ The move I played was dxe4, which happens to be the most commonly played move at my level.  The game went:   3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Nd7  5.Ngf3  e5  6.Nc4  Ngf6  7.Bg5  Qc7  8.Qe2  Be7  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Rd1  O-O  11.Nd6  Nb6  12.h3  Rd8  13.Qd3  a mistake, which led to a massive tradeoff and a win for Black. }
4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. g3
{ White hopes to fianchetto his Kingside Bishop so that it will be in a good position to attack Black's d5 pawn following a trade.  An alternative by White would be to play d4, which opens the center and results in Black having an isolated Queen pawn that cramps White's position.   5.d4  exd4  6.exd5  Nf6  7.dxc6  Nxc6  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  Bc7  evaluates to -0.1 }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4
{ A natural developing move that White will try to take advantage of. } 8. h3
Bh5
{ Trading for the Knight would not be good, as the Knight would only be replaces by another Knight, and the diagonal for White's dark-squared Bishop would open up. }
9. g4 Bg6
{ It appears that Black's Bishop is going nowhere, but if White's idea to fianchetto the Bishop was to have it available to help attack Black's d5 pawn, Black's Bishop is actually putting pressure on White's e4 pawn. }
10. Nh4
{ Moving aside for g2 Bishop and attacking Black's light-squared Bishop. }
10... Nbd7
{ Simply completing development.  If White chooses to remove Black's light-squared Bishop then that will not be a problem.  Another option for Black would have been to take the pawn.   10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.dxe4  g6 }
11. Nf5
{ The popular choice is to put the Knight on the doubly protected square.  Taking the Bishop is also possible followed with a Kingside attack, so Black should be prepared for that.   11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.g5  Nh5  13.exd5  cxd5  14.Bxd5  Nf4  Evaluation: -0.1 }
11... Bxf5 { Black removes the invasive Knight. } 12. gxf5 Re8
{ Evaluation: -0.4  Black holds a slight advantage but White has space.  Game in the database with this position:  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/VrJmvLtX@@LinkEnd@@ }
