[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "BONUS: The Oddballs"]
[Black "2. f4 - Bird Variation 6. c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. f4
{ It may appear to be a strange move, but is the most common second move for White outside of the main variations. }
2... d5
{ This will either end up resembling the Advanced Variation or the Classic Variation.  Exchanging is disadvantageous for White. }
3. e5
{ White overwhelmingly chooses the Advanced.  That said, I played an opponent who always plays e4 and f4 as White.  The beginning of the game went:   1.e4  c6  2.f4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Bd3  Bxd3  - better would have been e6 -  7.Qxd3  e6  8.O-O  Nc6  9.c3  Bd6  10.Ne5  O-O  11.Nd2  Nd7  12.Qg3  Ne7  13.Ndf3  Nf5  14.Qh3  and Black has a slight advantage. }
3... Bf5
{ Black has a number of alternatives here, like c5 and h5, but we should follow the idea of quickly developing our pieces.  This move gets the Bishop outside of the pawn structure. }
4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 c5
{ As is the case with the Advanced Variation, the idea is to attack White's pawn chain. }
6. c3 Nc6 { Adding additional pressure to d4. } 7. Bb5
{ The most common move for White, but Be2, Be3 and Qb3 would all have been much better. }
7... Qb6
{ h5 could be played here, as will be explained when we get to move 9.  There are other possibilities, but this immediately forces the question to White as to its intentions. }
8. Bxc6+ { White pretty much always takes, instead of the much stronger Qe2. }
8... bxc6
{ Taking with the b-pawn makes more sense than taking with the Queen, as Black has plans for the doubled pawn on this file. }
9. O-O h5
{ h5 could also have been played back at move 7, or even earlier.  Black's light-squared Bishop, which is usually something to toss, is now something to protect, as it has the long diagonal to itself. }
10. Nbd2 Nh6
{ This puts additional pressure on g4 in case White has thoughts of h3 then g4.  It also develops the Knight while allowing Black's dark-squared Bishop to patrol c5. }
11. Nb3
{ Of the four games in Lichess's database, three have White moving the Knight to b3.  It will not be there for long. }
11... c4
{ Taking more space, forcing the Knight to return to where it was, and setting future plans for the advance of Black's pawn on c6. }
12. Nbd2 Bd3
{ An aggressive move by White, invading Black's Kingside while commanding the full diagonal. }
13. Re1
{ The only game in the database can be found at @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/YKoVV1F4@@LinkEnd@@.  It is a fascinating game played by 1933 and 2089 players, where Black makes an incredible blunder for their final move, but White, apparently not recognizing the blunder, resigned.  In this position in that game, Black played Nf5, so the final move has no games in the database. }
13... Be7
{ Evaluation: -1.7  Black is on the attack while White is still trying to develop.  No games in this position. }
