[Black " 2. f4 - Bird Variation 6. c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. f4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 c5 6. c4
{ I encountered this variation in a recent game, so I decided to include it in the course. This is an uncommon move within an uncommon variation.  Interestingly, I had just gone over the Bird Variation before playing this game, but I was expecting the move c3, which is literally played 28 times more frequently.  Sometimes we just need to 'play chess.' }
6... dxc4
{ The strongest continuation - taking the other pawn is about one pawn weaker. }
7. Bxc4
{ A normal and expected move by White.  Stockfish says that either Nc3 or Be3 would be a better choice. }
7... Nc6
{ In the Caro-Kann we generally tend to develop the Kingside first, but the oddity of White's choice of 6. c4 within Bird's Variation dictates different choices.  This variation is not complementary to White, and the most popular moves will prove not to be the best. }
8. d5 { This is weaker than Be3, but played twice as often. } 8... exd5
{ Black's only move in this position.  Other moves lead to problems.  The second best move -   8...Bxb1  9.Rxb1  b5  10.Be2  Stockfish evaluates +1.5 if   10...exd5  , otherwise Black is lost.  All other moves lead Black to disaster. }
9. Bxd5 Nge7
{ Developing the Knight, attacking the Bishop, and protecting the other Knight. }
10. Nc3 Nxd5
{ Removing the Bishop and giving room for the dark squared Bishop to develop. }
11. Nxd5 c4
{ Evaluation: -3.1  There are no games in the Lichess database because in the four games offering the previous position, Black chose to play either the weaker Be6, Be4 or Be7. }
