[Black "2. c4 - Accelerated Panov Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 { The pawns at the center are going to go away. } 3. cxd5
cxd5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black loses two center pawns, White has an isolated Queen pawn.  The game will revolve around White trying to push that pawn and Black trying to block it. }
5. Nc3 Qd8
{ Black has other options that are all pretty much the same, Qa5, Qd7, Qd6, and even Qe6+.  There is nothing wrong with undeveloping at this point and starting from scratch.  White has an extra tempo, but it also has a targeted pawn it must protect at all costs. }
6. Nf3 g6
{ The Panov-Botvinnik Attack is one of the two previous openings in this course where Black fianchettoed the Kingside Bishop.  There are other options here that are equally plausible, like Nc6 and Nf6 where Black does not continue in this way, but it may be easy to remember if both similarly named openings follow the same path. }
7. d4 Bg7 8. Bc4 Nf6 9. O-O O-O { The Kingside is secure. } 10. h3 Nc6
{ h3 has been played, so Black needs to decide where to place the Bishop.  As the Knight needs to get out, that should happen first, and then perhaps a clue on Bishop placement will arrive. }
11. Be3 e6
{ Building a wall against the White light-squared Bishop, and making White's potential Qb3 less useful. }
12. Qd2
{ When one sees this alignment, the expectation is that the dark-squared Bishops will at some point leave the board. }
12... b6
{ Black's last move means that either the light-squared Bishop goes to d7, where it has no current role, or gets fianchettoed along with its sibling. }
13. Rad1 Bb7
{ Once the c6 Knight moves, Black will have a nice long diagonal on which to work. }
14. Bh6 Rc8
{ In the only game in Lichess's database, at @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/i7n3oVyl@@LinkEnd@@, Black played Nb4.  No need for Black to take, it is better to develop another piece and make White remove the Bishop. }
15. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ Evaluation: -0.1  An even game that will probably rest on the fate of White's isolated Queen pawn.  No games in this position. }
